      {
        "uuid": "msg_001",
        "sender": "human",
        "text": "Can you explain Python's asyncio library?",
        "created_at": "2024-03-10T09:00:30.000000Z",
        "updated_at": "2024-03-10T09:00:30.000000Z",
        "attachments": [],
        "files": []
      },
      {
        "uuid": "msg_002",
        "sender": "assistant",
        "text": "Python's asyncio library provides infrastructure for writing single-threaded concurrent code using coroutines. Key concepts include: event loops, coroutines (async/await), tasks, and futures. It's ideal for I/O-bound workloads like web requests and file operations.",
        "created_at": "2024-03-10T09:01:00.000000Z",
        "updated_at": "2024-03-10T09:01:00.000000Z",
        "attachments": [],
        "files": []
      },
      {
        "uuid": "msg_003",
        "sender": "human",
        "text": "What is the difference between asyncio.create_task and asyncio.ensure_future?",
        "created_at": "2024-03-10T09:05:00.000000Z",
        "updated_at": "2024-03-10T09:05:00.000000Z",
        "attachments": [],
        "files": []
      },
      {
        "uuid": "msg_004",
        "sender": "assistant",
        "text": "asyncio.create_task() is the modern, preferred way (Python 3.7+) to schedule a coroutine to run. asyncio.ensure_future() is older and more general — it accepts both coroutines and futures. Prefer create_task() for clarity in modern code.",
        "created_at": "2024-03-10T09:06:30.000000Z",
        "updated_at": "2024-03-10T09:06:30.000000Z",
        "attachments": [],
        "files": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "uuid": "claude_conv_002",
    "name": "Machine Learning Basics",
    "created_at": "2024-04-01T14:00:00.000000Z",
    "updated_at": "2024-04-01T14:20:00.000000Z",
    "account": {
      "uuid": "user_abc",
      "name": "Alice Coder"
    },
    "chat_messages": [
      {
        "uuid": "msg_005",
        "sender": "human",
        "text": "What is the difference between supervised and unsupervised learning?",
        "created_at": "2024-04-01T14:00:15.000000Z",
        "updated_at": "2024-04-01T14:00:15.000000Z",
        "attachments": [],
        "files": []
      },
      {
        "uuid": "msg_006",
        "sender": "assistant",
        "text": "Supervised learning uses labeled training data — you provide input-output pairs and the model learns the mapping. Examples: classification, regression. Unsupervised learning works with unlabeled data and finds hidden patterns. Examples: clustering, dimensionality reduction.",
        "created_at": "2024-04-01T14:01:00.000000Z",
        "updated_at": "2024-04-01T14:01:00.000000Z",
        "attachments": [],
        "files": []
      },
      {
        "uuid": "msg_007",
        "sender": "human",
        "text": "Which one should I use for anomaly detection?",
        "created_at": "2024-04-01T14:10:00.000000Z",
        "updated_at": "2024-04-01T14:10:00.000000Z",
        "attachments": [],
        "files": []
      },
      {
        "uuid": "msg_008",
        "sender": "assistant",
        "text": "For anomaly detection, unsupervised learning is typically preferred when labeled anomaly examples are scarce (which is common). Algorithms like Isolation Forest, Autoencoder, and One-Class SVM are popular choices. If you have labeled anomalies, a supervised approach can yield higher precision.",
        "created_at": "2024-04-01T14:12:00.000000Z",
        "updated_at": "2024-04-01T14:12:00.000000Z",
        "attachments": [],
        "files": []
      }
    ]
  },
